Conditional Statements

Conditional statements allow a program to make decisions.

The most common statement is if.

Example:

if(age >= 18)
{
    Console.WriteLine("Adult");
}

The else statement executes when the condition is false.

Example:

if(score >= 60)
{
    Console.WriteLine("Passed");
}
else
{
    Console.WriteLine("Failed");
}

When multiple conditions are needed, use else if.

switch is useful when comparing one variable with many possible values.

Example:

switch(day)
{
    case 1:
        Console.WriteLine("Monday");
        break;

    default:
        Console.WriteLine("Unknown");
        break;
}

Conditions usually use comparison operators:

==
!=
<
>
<=
>=

Logical operators include:

&&
||
!

Loops

Loops repeat code multiple times.

The for loop is used when the number of iterations is known.

Example:

for(int i = 0; i < 10; i++)
{
    Console.WriteLine(i);
}

The while loop repeats while a condition is true.

The do-while loop always executes at least once.

Example:

do
{
    Console.WriteLine("Running");
}
while(false);

foreach is used to iterate through collections.

Example:

foreach(string name in names)
{
    Console.WriteLine(name);
}

Choose the correct loop depending on the problem.

Methods

Methods are reusable blocks of code.

A method can receive parameters and return a value.

Example:

int Add(int a, int b)
{
    return a + b;
}

Methods improve code organization and reduce duplication.

Methods without a return value use void.

Example:

void PrintMessage()
{
    Console.WriteLine("Hello");
}

Parameters allow methods to work with different values.

Method names should describe their purpose clearly.

Inheritance

Inheritance allows one class to inherit members from another class.

The existing class is called the base class.

The new class is called the derived class.

Example:

class Animal
{
    public void Eat()
    {
    }
}

class Dog : Animal
{
}

Dog automatically inherits Eat().

Inheritance reduces duplicated code.

Only an "is-a" relationship should use inheritance.

Examples:

Dog is an Animal.

Car is not an Engine.

Interfaces

An interface defines a contract.

It contains method declarations but normally no implementation.

Example:

interface IMovable
{
    void Move();
}

A class implements the interface.

Example:

class Car : IMovable
{
    public void Move()
    {
        Console.WriteLine("Moving");
    }
}

Interfaces allow different classes to share the same behavior.

A class may implement multiple interfaces.

Interfaces increase flexibility and make testing easier.
